value.value: A variant of ovarian thecoma characterized by the presence of lutein cells. It is associated with a lower frequency of estrogenic manifestations compared to typical thecomas. In a minority of cases androgenic manifestations are present.

A benign ovarian stromal tumor characterized by the presence of cellular areas which contain fibroblasts and round cells. The cellular areas are separated by sclerotic or edematous hypocellular tissue. Symptoms include abdominal discomfort and menstrual abnormalities.
A neuroblastoma characterized by the absence of differentiating neuroblasts.
A neuroblastoma in which the differentiating neuroblasts constitute less than five-percent of the tumor cells.
A neuroblastoma in which the differentiating neuroblasts constitute more than five-percent of the tumor cells.
A finding indicating the presence of a Schwann cell-rich stromal component in a neoplastic tissue specimen.
A granulosa cell tumor which has an aggressive clinical course and metastasizes to other anatomic sites.
An embryonic cell on the dorsal surface of the early vertebrate embryo that gives rise to the cells of the nervous system

label.value: Differentiating Neuroblasts Under 5 Percent of the Tumor Cells
Differentiating Neuroblasts More than 5 Percent of the Tumor Cells

value.value: A monoclonal antibody directed against the neurohormone bombesin that is conjugated to diethylenetriaminepenta-acetic acid (DPTA), a bifunctional chelating agent that allows the antibody to be labeled with a metal species such as radioactive indium.  Levels of bombesin, also known as gastrin releasing peptide (GRP), are elevated in lung and thyroid cancers, where the substance acts as an autocrine growth factor. (NCI04)

A monoclonal antibody directed against the neurohormone bombesin that is conjugated to isothiocyanobenzyl diethylenetriaminepentaacetic acid (ITC-D), a bifunctional chelating agent that allows the antibody to be labeled with a metal species. Levels of the neurohormone bombesin, also known as gastrin releasing peptide (GRP), are elevated in lung and thyroid cancers, where the substance acts as an autocrine growth factor. (NCI04)
A ganglioneuroblastoma characterized by the presence of neuroblastic cells in a Schwannian stroma, without the presence of hemorrhagic neuroblastic nodules.
A ganglioneuroblastoma characterized by the presence of neuroblastic cells in a Schwannian stroma, and the formation of hemorrhagic neuroblastic nodules.

label.value: Composite Ganglioneuroblastoma, Schwannian Stroma-Rich and Stroma-Poor

value.value: A neuroblastic tumor characterized by the presence of a ganglioneuroblastoma component and the formation of Schwannian stroma which constitutes more than fifty-percent of the tumor volume.
A neuroblastic tumor characterized by the presence of a ganglioneuroblastoma component and the formation of Schwannian stroma which is the predominant component of the tumor volume.

label.value: Schwannian Stroma More than 50 Percent of the Tumor Volume
Schwannian Stroma Predominant Component of the Tumor Volume

value.value: A ganglioneuroma characterized by the presence of differentiating neuroblasts, maturing and mature ganglion cells.
A ganglioneuroma characterized by the presence of mature ganglion cells and a mature Schwannian stroma.
